<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[DCR Pt 2 r 4] r 4 Registries">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4" type="ext"/>[DCR Pt 2 r 4]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Registries</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>4</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The registry for each proclaimed place shall be under the control and direction of the registrar for the place, subject to any direction by the Chief Judge or a Judge.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="true" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[subr (2)  rep Gaz 97 of 18 August 1978  p 3465]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="true" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[subr (3)  rep Gaz 97 of 18 August 1978  p 3465]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4" type="ext"/>(4)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Except on Saturdays, Sundays and other holidays, and whether in vacation or not:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4.A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4.A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>the registry for Sydney shall be open to the public for business between 9.30 in the morning and 4.00 in the afternoon, and</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4.B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4.B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>the registry for any other proclaimed place shall be open to the public for business between 9.30 in the morning and 1.00 in the afternoon, and between 2.00 and 4.00 in the afternoon.</text></p>
</li>
</l>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>DCR r 102A</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>DCR r 3</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note><leg:histnote>
<p><text>[subr (4)  am Gaz 97 of 18 August 1978  p 3465 ; Gaz 122 of 30 August 1985  p 4621]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.5"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.5" type="ext"/>(5)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A registry shall, notwithstanding 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.4" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">subrule (4)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
, be kept open to the public for business, or closed for business, at such times on such days as the Chief Judge or a Judge shall direct.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>DCR r 4</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.DC.DCRN.PT2.R4.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_DC.SGM_UCPN.DC.PT2.R4-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[DCR Pt 2 r 4.5] Registry practice"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.DC.PT2.R4-5" type="ext"/>[DCR Pt 2 r 4.5] </edpnum><title>Registry practice</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text><emph typestyle="it">Certification of claims and defences</emph> &#x2003;On 19 August 2002, the court by announced the procedures under which Certificates under 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.OL.LPAN.S198L" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID" status="unval">s 198L</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Legal Profession Act 1987 were to be dealt with in the Sydney Registry. The provisions of the former s. 198L are now contained in s. 347 of the Legal Profession Act 2004. Specifically, s 347(2) prohibits the filing of Court documentation in the absence of the appropriate certification that the claim or defence has reasonable prospects of success. The procedures adopted in the Registry are as follows and apply to proceedings commenced on or after 18 August 2002:</text>
<l>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>For statements of claim &#x2014; certificates are mandatory in damages claims filed by a legal practitioner. Certificates are not required for debt claims.</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>For defences &#x2014; certificates are mandatory where a defence is filed by a legal practitioner on a statement of claim for damages.</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>For cross-claims &#x2014; certificates are mandatory where a cross-claim for damages is being filed on a statement of claim.</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>For defences to cross-claims &#x2014; certificates are mandatory on defences to cross-claims for damages.</text></p></li></l></p>
<p>
<text>Generally: the certificate can be a separate document, or it can be endorsed on the statement of claim; if there is no certificate,</text>
<l>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>a written undertaking to supply one within seven days is acceptable;</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>a fax of an undertaking is acceptable;</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>litigants in person are not required to file a certificate; and</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>appeals, certificates of judgments and applications/motions do not require a certification.</text></p></li></l></p>
<p>
<text><emph typestyle="it">Fees</emph> &#x2003;As from 3 July 2000, the court announced that private cheques will not be accepted for payment of court fees by the Sydney registry. However, cheques drawn on practitioners accounts continue to be accepted.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
